  <em>Example, Flag of <a href="es-av-al.html">Aldeanueva de Santa Cruz</a>, Spain (fotw); Arms of 
  <a href="pt-stcsv.html">S�o Domingos e Vale de �gua</a>, Portugal (fotw)  </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="doubleapplique"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE APPLIQU&#201;</dt>
  <dd>A term that may be used when the appliqu� technique is applied to both sides of a flag � 
  see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva3.html#applique">appliqu&#233;</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs4.html#singleapplique">single appliqu&#233;</a>&rsquo;).
  </dd>  
  
  <hr /><a name="doublearmedcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE-ARMED CROSS</dt>
  <dd>1) A less ambiguous interpretation of the German term <em>Doppelkreux</em> - see �<a href="#doublecross">double cross 
  2)</a>�)  . 
  <br>
  2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crosslorraine">cross of Lorraine</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4063a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4063a.gif" alt="double-armed cross" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4063.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4063.gif" alt="double-armed cross" border="0" height="108" /></a><br/>
  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pl-ma-sk.html">Skaryszew</a>, Poland (fotw)</em></p>
  </dd>

  <hr />
  <a name="doubleborder"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE BORDER </dt>
  <dd>A term that may be used when a flag has two borders � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#innerborder">inner border 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#outerborder">outer border</a>&rsquo;.     
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2095.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2095.gif" alt="[example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>Former Flag of <a href="gr-mh-av.html#vis">Vistonida</a>, Greece (fotw)</em>
  </dd>


  <hr />
  <a name="doublecotticed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE COTTICED (or COTISED) </dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#cotticed">cotticed 2)</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1164b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1164b.gif" alt="[example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="doublecross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE CROSS</dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcs.html#crosslorraine">Cross of Lorraine</a>&rsquo;.<br> 
  2) A direct translation of the German term <em>Doppelkreux</em> � but see the note below.
  <br>3) The colloquial term for a treacherous act, and (appropriately) used in one instance to 
  illustrate the charge on a fictitious flag as shown below - 
  see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#twinsaltires">twin saltires</a>&rsquo;.&nbsp;
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d2412.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2412.gif" alt="Slovakia" border="0" height="106" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2412a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2412a.gif" alt="Slovakia" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2413.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2413.gif" alt="Tomania" border="0" height="106" /></a><em>
  <br>National Flag and Arms of <a href="sk.html">Slovakia</a> (fotw); 
  National Flag of the fictitious country <a href="fic_dict.html#flag">Tomania</a> from the film The Great Dictator (fotw)
  <p>
  Please note regarding 2) that this term is (as may be seen above) slightly ambiguous, and therefore, the Editors suggest use of the phrase �double-armed cross� as being more accurate.</em>
    </dd>
 
  <hr /><a name="doublefimbriated"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE-FIMBRIATED</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#cotticed">cotticed 1)</a>&rsquo; and its following note (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf1.html#fimbriation">fimbriated</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1397.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1397.gif" alt="example" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d852.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d852.gif" alt="Rudervereinigung Hellas-Titania, Germany" border="0" height="108" /></a><br/>
  <em>Example; Flag of Rudervereinigung <a href="de@ht.html">Hellas-Titania</a>, Germany (fotw)</em></p></dd>

  <hr /><a name="doublepavon"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE PAVON (or DOUBLE PENNANT)</dt>
  <dd>Alternative terms for the shape of the national flag of Nepal, which was apparently created by two pavon-style pennants having been sewn together - see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#pavon">pavon</a>&rsquo; 
  (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d607.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d607.gif" alt="Nepal" border="0" width="88" height="106" /></a> 
   <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2871.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2871.gif" alt="Dewaas" border="0" width="106" height="106" /></a> 
   <a href="../images/v/vxt-d607a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d607a.gif" alt="Dewaas" border="0" width="106" height="106" /></a><br />
    <em>National Flag of <a href="np.html">Nepal</a> (fotw); Flag of 
  <a href="np-kir.html">Kirat</a>, Nepal (fotw); Former Princely State of 
  <a href="in-dewas.html">Dewas</a>,
   India (fotw)</em>
  <p><em>Please note regarding the main heading above, that these terms have been introduced by the Editors as a more accurate alternatives to that already introduced.</em></p></dd>

  <hr /><a name="doublepointed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE-POINTED</dt>
  <dd>A term for that variation of the swallow-tailed flag where a vertical section appears 
  in the centre of the fly (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs5.html#splittflag">splittflag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail">swallow-tail(ed)</a>&rsquo; (also �<a href="vxt-dvt4.html#triangulartongued">triangular-tongued</a>�). 
  <p class="style1"><a href="../images/v/vxt-d527.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d527.gif" alt="Denmark yacht ensign" border="0" width="202" height="106" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d527a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d527a.gif" alt="[Iceland]" border="0" width="188" height="106" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d527b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d527b.gif" alt="[Aaland Islands yacht ensign]" border="0" width="193" height="106" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>The Yacht Ensign of <a href="dk-yacht.html#yf">Denmark</a> (fotw); 
  State Flag of <a href="is-gov.html#state">Iceland</a> (fotw); Yacht Ensign of the 
  <a href="ax@yt.html">Aaland Is</a>,, Finland (fotw)</em>
  
  <hr /><a name="doubleprince"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE-PRINCE</dt>
  <dd>The term for a 17th Century Dutch naval flag usually (but not invariably) of six even, horizontal stripes 
  in the Dutch national colours repeated &ndash; but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tripleprince">triple-prince</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#dreikleur">dreikleur</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp6.html#princeflag">princeflag</a>&rsquo;)   <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d121.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d121.gif" alt="[double prince]" border="0" width="159" height="106"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d634a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d634a.gif" alt="double prince with 7 stripes" border="0" height="106" /></a>
  <br />  <em>From left: <a href="nl_prvlg.html#6">Double Prince</a> c1660 (fotw); With 
  <a href="nl_prvlg.html#7">Seven Stripes</a> c1660 (fotw)</em>
  <p><em>Please note however, whilst all available evidence 
  suggests that red, white and blue were employed, orange instead of red may 
  have been used at an earlier stage. </em> </p>
  </dd>
     
  <hr /><a name="doublequeued"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE QUEUED</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term used when a lion is showing a double tail &ndash; a queue fourch&eacute; or 
  fourch&eacute;e (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvco.html#coward">coward</a>&rsquo;, 
  �<a href="vxt-dvf6.html#fourche">fourch&#233;</a>� and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#queued">queued</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4451.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4451.gif" alt="double queued" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d767b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d767b.gif" alt="double queued" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4536.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4536.gif" alt="double queued" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="ch-vs076.html">Martigny</a>, Switzerland (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="be-wlgsv.html">Sankt Vith</a>, Belgium (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="ch-bl010.html">Muttenz</a>, Switzerland (fotw)
  </em></dd> 

  <hr /><a name="double-sided"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE-SIDED</dt>
  <dd>1) The term used when a flag is made from two separate pieces of cloth placed back to back, 
  either to ensure that the reverse of a flag is not a mirror image of the obverse (as in the 
  National Flag of Saudi Arabia) or (in the case of some military colours and others) is of a 
  different design (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvm3.html#mirrorimage">mirror image</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-o.html#obverse">obverse</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#reverse">reverse</a>&rsquo;).
  <br>
  2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt6.html#two-sided">two-sided 1)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3539.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3539.gif" alt="[double-sided example]" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3540.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3540.gif" alt="[double-sided example]" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1446a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1446a.gif" alt="[double-sided example]" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1446b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1446b.gif" alt="[double-sided example]" border="0" height="108"/></a><br /><em>The Obverse and Reverse of the National, double-sided Flag of   
  <a href="md.html">Moldova</a> 1990-2010 (fotw & CS); Obverse and Reverse, Colour of <a href="es^civil.html#con">The Condor Legion</a>, Spain 1939 (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="doubleswallowtail"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">DOUBLE-SWALLOWTAIL</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail-tongue">swallowtail and tongue</a>&rsquo;
  and �<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tripletailed">triple-tailed 1)</a>�.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3842.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3842.gif" alt="swallowtail" border="0" height="108" /></a>
